<section id="classification">

<h2>What is Classification?</h2>

<p>
Classification is the scientific process of arranging living organisms
into different groups according to their similarities and differences.
It helps scientists identify organisms easily and understand their
relationships and evolution.
</p>

<div class="highlight">
<b>Importance of Classification</b>
<ul>
<li>Helps identify organisms correctly.</li>
<li>Makes the study of biology easier.</li>
<li>Shows evolutionary relationships.</li>
<li>Avoids confusion caused by local names.</li>
<li>Provides a universal system for scientists.</li>
</ul>
</div>

</section>

<section id="fivekingdom">

<h2>Five Kingdom Classification</h2>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Kingdom</th>
<th>Main Features</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Monera</td>
<td>Single-celled organisms without a true nucleus.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Protista</td>
<td>Mostly unicellular organisms with a true nucleus.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Fungi</td>
<td>Non-green organisms that absorb nutrients from other materials.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Plantae</td>
<td>Green multicellular organisms capable of photosynthesis.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Animalia</td>
<td>Multicellular organisms that cannot prepare their own food.</td>
</tr>

</table>

</section>

<section id="plantae">

<h2>Kingdom Plantae</h2>

<p>
Kingdom Plantae includes all green plants ranging from tiny mosses to
large flowering trees. Plants contain chlorophyll, which enables them
to make food through photosynthesis using sunlight, water, and carbon
dioxide.
</p>

<p>
Plants are essential for life because they produce oxygen, provide food,
medicine, timber, paper, fibers, and maintain ecological balance.
</p>

</section>

<section id="characteristics">

<h2>Characteristics of Kingdom Plantae</h2>

<ul>
<li>Plants are multicellular organisms.</li>
<li>Cells have a true nucleus.</li>
<li>Cell walls are made of cellulose.</li>
<li>Plants contain chloroplasts with chlorophyll.</li>
<li>They prepare food by photosynthesis.</li>
<li>They are autotrophic in nutrition.</li>
<li>Food is stored mainly as starch.</li>
<li>Most plants are fixed in one place.</li>
<li>They reproduce by seeds, spores, or vegetative methods.</li>
<li>Most plants have roots, stems, and leaves.</li>
<li>Plants require sunlight, water, carbon dioxide, and minerals for growth.</li>
<li>They play an important role in maintaining oxygen and carbon dioxide balance.</li>
</ul>

</section>

<section>

<h2>Importance of Plants</h2>

<ul>
<li>Produce oxygen for living organisms.</li>
<li>Provide food for humans and animals.</li>
<li>Prevent soil erosion.</li>
<li>Supply medicines.</li>
<li>Provide wood, paper, rubber, cotton, and fibers.</li>
<li>Help regulate climate.</li>
<li>Provide habitat for many animals.</li>
</ul>

</section>

<section>

<h2>Conclusion</h2>

<p>
The classification of living beings helps scientists organize and study
the enormous variety of organisms found on Earth. Kingdom Plantae is one
of the five kingdoms and consists of green, multicellular, autotrophic
organisms. Plants are indispensable because they provide food, oxygen,
shelter, medicines, and numerous resources while maintaining ecological
balance on our planet.
</p>

</section>

